,"–Female":"Overleden","1332–1370":"1332–1370","1369–Male":"1369–Overleden","1371–Male":"1371–Overleden","1373–Male":"1373–Overleden","1355–1417":"1355–1417","1330–1384":"1330–1384","about 1371":"circa 1371","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1369":"1369","by 1370":"1370","1355":"1355","about 1369":"circa 1369","1332":"1332","about 1356":"circa 1356","1382-1384":"van 1382 to 1384","about 1355":"circa 1355","about 1330":"circa 1330","1417":"1417","about 1373":"circa 1373","England":"England","Seagry, Wiltshire, England":"Seagry, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Seagry, Wiltshire, England":"Seagry, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1330–1382-1384":"about 1330–from 1382 to 1384","–Female":"Deceased","1332–1370":"1332–1370","1369–Male":"1369–Deceased","1371–Male":"1371–Deceased","1373–Male":"1373–Deceased","1355–1417":"1355–1417","1330–1384":"1330–1384","about 1371":"about 1371","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1369":"1369","by 1370":"1370","1355":"1355","about 1369":"about 1369","1332":"1332","about 1356":"about 1356","1382-1384":"from 1382 to 1384","about 1355":"about 1355","about 1330":"about 1330","1417":"1417","about 1373":"about 1373","England":"England","Seagry, Wiltshire, England":"Seagry, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","of Seagry, Wiltshire, England":"Seagry, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from a Norman French personal name <i>Dreus</i> based on ancient Germanic <i>Drogo</i>, the name of one of the sons of Charlemagne (compare Gothic <i>driugan</i> ‘to serve as a soldier’). In Old French this name became <i>Dreus</i>, <i>Drues</i> (nominative) and <i>Dru</i>, <i>Driu</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (accusative) and was introduced to England by the Normans. For further information about this name, see also   Montague  .","English: from the personal name <i>Drew</i>, a pet form of   Andrew   which was confused with the same name of Old French origin (see 1 above).","Irish: when not an adoption of the English surname, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Draoi</b> ‘son’ and ‘descendant of the druid’, from <i>draoi</i> ‘druid’, genitive <i>druadh</i> or <i>draoi</i>. All of these were often Anglicized as   Drury  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Drews","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Gerhard, Gunter, Hans, Heinz, Helmut, Otto, Reinhold, Bernd, Detlef, Egon, Erna.","English: variant of   Drew   with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also found in Guernsey in the Channel Islands.","Americanized form of German, Danish, and Dutch   Drewes  ."]},{"name":"Drewer","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Droart</i>, <i>Drouart</i> (which is probably from ancient Germanic <i>Droghard</i>, with the first element as in   Drew   + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy’)."]},{"name":"Drewett","meanings":["English (Wiltshire, Berkshire, and Surrey): of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Druet</i>, a diminutive of <i>Drue</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Drogo</i>); see   Drew   1. Alternatively, the name may be from a diminutive of Old French <i>dru</i> ‘lover’; see   Drew   4."]},{"name":"Dronet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcee, Desire, Olympe.","French (mainly Loire-Atlantique): from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Dron</i>, derived from the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  )."]},{"name":"Droz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Aida, Cruz Maria, Diego, Jose, Miguel, Milagros, Nydia, Osvaldo, Rodriguez, Vidal.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  ). This surname is also found in Puerto Rico."]},{"name":"Drea","meanings":["Irish (Kilkenny): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Draoi</b> (see   Drew  )."]},{"name":"Montague","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either Montaigu-le-bois (Manche) or Montaigu (Manche, Aisne), named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>agu</i> ‘pointed’ (from Latin <i>acutus</i>). Drogo de Montagud was a companion of William the Conqueror and founder of the <b>Montagu(e)</b> family, among whom the personal name <i>Drogo</i> was revived in the 19th century. Another family of the name <b>Monatgu</b> have held the titles of Duke of Montagu, Earl of Sandwich, Earl and Duke of Manchester, Earl of Halifax, and Earl of Beaulieu, and.","Irish: adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b> (see   McTigue  )."]},{"name":"Drouin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Benoit, Jacques, Andre, Clermont, Emile, Gaston, Gilles, Ovide, Pierre, Serge.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Droue</i>, a variant of <i>Dreue</i>, which is from the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  ). Compare   Derouen  ,   Derouin  , and   Tron  ."]},{"name":"Drury","meanings":["Anglo-Norman: Druerie, courtship, gallantry, love"]},{"name":"Drouhard","meanings":["French:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Droghard</i>, composed of the elements <i>drog</i> (presumably meaning ‘battle’; see also   Drew  ) and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’.","alternatively, a derivative of the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names like <i>Droghard</i> (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Drew was born about 1330, in Seagry, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Joan Maufitz about 1356, in Seagry, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died from 1382 to 1384."},"et":{"about 1330–1382-1384":"umbes 1330–1382 kuni 1384","–Female":"Surnud","1332–1370":"1332–1370","1369–Male":"1369–Surnud","1371–Male":"1371–Surnud","1373–Male":"1373–Surnud","1355–1417":"1355–1417","1330–1384":"1330–1384","about 1371":"umbes 1371","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1369":"1369","by 1370":"1370","1355":"1355","about 1369":"umbes 1369","1332":"1332","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1382-1384":"1382 kuni 1384","about 1355":"umbes 1355","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1417":"1417","about 1373":"umbes 1373","England":"England","Seagry, Wiltshire, England":"Seagry, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Seagry, Wiltshire, England":"Seagry, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1330–1382-1384":"noin 1330–vuodesta 1382 vuoteen 1384","–Female":"Kuollut","1332–1370":"1332–1370","1369–Male":"1369–Kuollut","1371–Male":"1371–Kuollut","1373–Male":"1373–Kuollut","1355–1417":"1355–1417","1330–1384":"1330–1384","about 1371":"noin 1371","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1369":"1369","by 1370":"1370","1355":"1355","about 1369":"noin 1369","1332":"1332","about 1356":"noin 1356","1382-1384":"v